You can't have two types with the same name. You can rename one of them, or merge them into a single type that covers both cases:

```typescript
export type RefProps = {
  contactref?: React.MutableRefObject<null>;
  skillref?: React.MutableRefObject<null>;
}
```

This defines a `RefProps` type with two optional properties, `contactref` and `skillref`, that are both an optional mutable reference to `null`.

Yes, you can make it more generic by using a generic parameter for the `React.MutableRefObject` type:

```typescript
export type RefProps<T> = {
  ref: React.MutableRefObject<T | null>;
}
```

This defines a generic `RefProps` type that takes a type parameter `T`, and requires a single property `ref` that's a mutable reference to `null` or a value of type `T`. You can use this type to define specific ref properties:

```typescript
// Example usage:
type MyComponentProps = {
  contactRef: RefProps<HTMLDivElement>,
  skillRef: RefProps<HTMLInputElement>,
}
``` 

This defines a type `MyComponentProps` with two properties, `contactRef` and `skillRef`, that are both of type `RefProps` with different `T` type parameters.

type MyComponentProps = {
  contactRef?: React.MutableRefObject<HTMLDivElement | null>,
  skillRef?: React.MutableRefObject<HTMLInputElement | null>,
}
use less code React.MutableRefObject<HTMLDivElement | null> is doubled

You can further reduce the code by extracting the type `React.MutableRefObject<T | null>` to a type alias and using it in the `MyComponentProps` type:

```typescript
type Ref<T> = React.MutableRefObject<T | null>;

type MyComponentProps = {
  contactRef?: Ref<HTMLDivElement>,
  skillRef?: Ref<HTMLInputElement>,
}
```

This defines a generic `Ref` type alias for a mutable reference that can either be `null` or have a value of type `T`. The `MyComponentProps` type uses this alias to define the `contactRef` and `skillRef` properties, which are both optional and can hold a mutable reference to a specific type of DOM element. 

This approach avoids duplicating the `React.MutableRefObject<T | null>` type signature in the `MyComponentProps` type, and also allows you to reuse the `Ref` alias in other parts of the code.

type MyComponentProps = {
  contactRef?: Ref<HTMLDivElement>,
  skillRef?: Ref<HTMLInputElement>,
}
